# ROADMAP-V4: Live AWS deployment for the 50 most-used AWS services

## Context

IaP v0.1.0 can plan/analyze 8 AWS-mapped kinds but live-deploy only 3 target types (`aws:s3:Bucket`, `aws:sqs:Queue`, `aws:iam:Role`) — everything else fails closed (`SUPPORTED_TARGET_TYPES` in `packages/deploy-aws/src/types.ts:9`). The user wants a roadmap (documents only, no implementation now) to extend live deployment to the ~50 most-used AWS services.

Decisions already made by the user:
- Count = **50 AWS services** (≈ 90–120 target-type handlers, since one service often needs several).
- **Spec work is in scope** (graduating reserved kinds, adding new core kinds via additive spec minors).
- Verification bar: **every handler mock-tested (aws-sdk-client-mock) + one live golden-path run per wave** on cheap resources with full teardown and an evidence doc; every live run and spec minor is a human-approval gate.
- Deliverable: **roadmap documents only**; implementation happens later milestone-by-milestone.

Key architecture facts the roadmap builds on (verified in code):
- Two layers: mapping artifact `providers/aws/mappings/core.iap-map.yaml` (signed, fail-closed, already emits ~13 target types) and runtime `packages/deploy-aws/` (TargetHandler contract: `read/desiredProjection/create/update/delete`, hardcoded handler Map, eager one-client-per-service `clients.ts`).
- CLI/state/drift/planner are target-type-agnostic — expansion lives in `packages/deploy-aws/` + mapping YAML + spec.
- `extensions.aws` can never add vocabulary (Non-Interference Rule); new services need core-kind fit or a spec minor. 13 core kinds exist; 9 reserved kinds (Network, Certificate, DnsZone, Stream, Workflow, SearchIndex, Registry, Dashboard, Alert) need graduation via additive `1.x.0` releases.
- Replacement-update semantics were deferred in the M19.3 live run and become blocking at DynamoDB — must land in the foundation milestone.

